6. Packages and Access Control

Q1. Create a user-defined package mathops with a class Operations having methods add (),
subtract (). Import it into another class and use it.

package mathops;
public class Operations {
    public int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
    public int subtract(int a, int b) { return a - b; }
}

import mathops.Operations;
public class MainTest {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Operations op = new Operations();
        System.out.println("Add: " + op.add(10, 5));
        System.out.println("Subtract: " + op.subtract(10, 5));
    }
}

Q2. Show the use of all access modifiers (private, public, protected, and default) by creating
variables and methods in different classes.
class Demo {
    public int pub = 10;
    private int pri = 20;
    protected int pro = 30;
    int def = 40; // default

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Public: " + pub);
        System.out.println("Private: " + pri);
        System.out.println("Protected: " + pro);
        System.out.println("Default: " + def);
    }
}

public class AccessDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo d = new Demo();
        d.show();
        System.out.println("Accessing Public: " + d.pub);
        // System.out.println(d.pri); // ‚ùå private - not accessible
        System.out.println("Protected: " + d.pro); // works (same package)
        System.out.println("Default: " + d.def);   // works (same package)
    }
}

Q3. Create two packages: package1 with class A and package2 with class B. Access class A
from B using import.

package package1;
public class A {
    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Hello from Class A in package1");
    }
}

package package2;
import package1.A; // importing class A
public class B {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        A obj = new A();
        obj.display();
    }
}
